00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:42.376
This is a tracing of the sales
volume of Polaroid from 1957

00:08:42.376 --> 00:08:47.288
until the firm's demise.
 

00:08:47.288 --> 00:08:53.346
One of the things you can--that
is of interest about this

00:08:53.346 --> 00:08:59.404
diagram, is that the sales at
death were not dramatically

00:08:59.404 --> 00:09:02.649
below their all time peak.
 

00:09:02.649 --> 00:09:11.006
So sales alone don't tell you
enough to understand what

00:09:11.006 --> 00:09:12.710
happened.
 

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:20.011
This is the stock price,
and this is--what are stock

00:09:20.011 --> 00:09:22.159
prices about?
 

00:09:22.159 --> 00:09:29.750
What are the drivers?
 

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:31.558
I'm not asking for anything
fancy here.

00:09:31.558 --> 00:09:34.519
What are the drivers--yes,
back left.

00:09:34.519 --> 00:09:39.279
Student:  It's expected
future dividends.

00:09:39.279 --> 00:09:42.702
Prof: Okay,
expected future earnings,

00:09:42.702 --> 00:09:46.923
along with some special sauce
having to do with future

00:09:46.923 --> 00:09:49.870
strategy to maintain share
price.

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:53.710
Student:  Interest rates.
 

00:09:53.710 --> 00:09:57.658
Prof: How would interest
rates play into this?

00:09:57.658 --> 00:10:00.556
Student:  Basically,
formulaically,

00:10:00.556 --> 00:10:04.575
the expectations--
Prof: Okay--just for

00:10:04.575 --> 00:10:09.739
those of us who are from
Illinois, spell it out a little

00:10:09.739 --> 00:10:10.960
at a time.
 

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:12.000
Who's from Illinois here?
 

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.788
I apologize.
 

00:10:13.788 --> 00:10:18.269
Hell, I should have said
Indiana, I'm from there.

00:10:18.269 --> 00:10:20.960
Okay, spell it out for us.
 

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:24.264
Student:  A lower
interest rate will yield a

00:10:24.264 --> 00:10:28.096
higher stock price because there
will be less of a tradeoff

00:10:28.096 --> 00:10:31.600
between spending today and what
you get tomorrow.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:34.860
Prof: Well, sort of.
 

00:10:34.860 --> 00:10:39.158
Jim do you want to help with
that?

00:10:39.158 --> 00:10:43.230
Jim Alexander:
 They really are a

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:48.970
projection of future cash flows
to the shareholders,

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:51.970
it's just that it used to be in
the 1950s,

00:10:51.970 --> 00:10:55.495
1960s, and 1970s,
dividends that were the bulk of

00:10:55.495 --> 00:10:59.062
those assumptions,
and today it's a rare company

00:10:59.062 --> 00:11:02.971
that makes more than 1% or 2%
dividend yield on the stock

00:11:02.971 --> 00:11:03.600
price.
 

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:06.509
So really it's a projection of
earnings which is encapsulated.

00:11:06.509 --> 00:11:10.744
When you look at that chart,
what you see is the typical

00:11:10.744 --> 00:11:15.364
problem with a lot of growth
stocks and that is people buying

00:11:15.364 --> 00:11:19.828
onto a whole new paradigm and
then extrapolates for decades

00:11:19.828 --> 00:11:23.909
and you end up with a stock
price that really bears no

00:11:23.909 --> 00:11:26.990
resemblance to current earnings.
 

00:11:26.990 --> 00:11:29.138
Prof: And an increase in
interest rates,

00:11:29.138 --> 00:11:31.090
how would that view--
Jim Alexander:

00:11:31.090 --> 00:11:33.202
 That would--
an increase in--all of the

00:11:33.202 --> 00:11:35.943
things being equal--
an increase in current interest

00:11:35.943 --> 00:11:39.206
rates would lower the stock
price because you would have to

00:11:39.206 --> 00:11:42.639
be compensated for the extra
time value of money involved.

00:11:42.639 --> 00:11:45.149
Prof: Thanks.
 

00:11:45.149 --> 00:11:53.988
Sales, this is a curve in red
that we saw in the first slide,

